== Geography and climate ==
At the foot of Bear Mountain ridge, the city developed around the Dawson Creek watercourse which flows eastward into the [[Pouce Coupe River]]. The city is located on the Pouce Coupe Prairie in the southwestern part of the [[Peace River Country]], {{convert|72|km|abbr=on|1}} southeast of Fort St. John, and {{convert|134|km|abbr=on|1}} northwest of Grande Prairie, Alberta. According to the [[Canada Land Inventory]], the city is on soil that has moderate limitations, due to an adverse climate, that restrict the range of crops or require moderate conservation practices.<ref>[http://www.alc.gov.bc.ca/alr/ag_cap_details.htm#class Agriculture Capability Detailed Description.] Provincial Agricultural Land Commission. Retrieved 17 November 2005.</ref> The land is flat, but slopes upwards in the northeastern corner elevating a residential area over the rest of the city.

The city is in the British Columbia Peace Lowland ecosection of the [[Boreal Plains|Canadian Boreal Plains]] [[ecozone]] on the continental [[Interior Plains|Interior Platform]]. Located in the Cordillera Climatic Region, it lies at the southern end of a [[subarctic climate]] ([[K<U+00F6>ppen climate classification|K<U+00F6>ppen]] ''Dfc''). In the summer, the city is often dusty and arid; temperatures during the day are warm, but cool at night, typically falling below {{convert|10|<U+00B0>C}}. Highs reaching {{convert|30|<U+00B0>C}} occur only twice per year on average. Heavy rain showers are sporadic, lasting only a few minutes. In the winter, the city can get bitterly cold and dry, with 17 to 18 days of {{convert|-30|<U+00B0>C}} lows per year. It is subject to very strong winds year round.<ref>[http://www.peaceenergy.ca/windpower.html Wind Power.] Peace Energy Co-op. Retrieved 20 November 2005.</ref> Unlike [[Time in Canada#Mountain Time Zone|most of the province]], the city and its region use [[Mountain Time Zone|Mountain Standard Time]] ([[UTC<U+2212>07:00]]) all year round, since the area already has long daylight hours in the summer and short daylight hours in the winter. In other words, residents of the region never change their clocks - they use [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific Daylight Time]] during the spring and summer, and Mountain Standard Time during the fall and winter.<ref name="CFS">{{CFS}}</ref>

