== Economy ==
The economy of Dawson Creek is based around four major industries: agriculture, retail, tourism, and oil and gas.<ref name=BCmag>{{cite news |first=J.B. |last=MacKinnon |title=Dawson Creek: Mile Zero, where the buffalo roam |work=British Columbia Magazine |date=Fall 2005 |pages=17<U+2013>19}}</ref> Agriculture has historically been the most important industry to Dawson Creek, as the city is the regional transshipment point for agricultural commodities. The city is surrounded by the [[Agricultural Land Reserve]], where the soil can support livestock and produces consistently good yields of quality grain and grass crops, such as canola, hay, oats, alfalfa, wheat, and sweet clover.<ref>Harry Giles, Dawson Creek, [http://www.calverley.ca/Part05-Dawson%20Creek/5-002.html "The Cross Roads of the North"] The Vancouver Province, 1953.</ref> The service and retail sector caters to the city's inhabitants, smaller nearby towns, and rural communities. However, there is significant [[leakage effect|retail leakage]] to Grande Prairie, the closest major Alberta city, where there is no [[Sales taxes in Canada|provincial tax]] on retail purchases, while British Columbia charges 7%.<ref>{{cite news |first=Terry |last=O'Neill |title=Exasperation in B.C. |work=Newsmagazine (Alberta Edition) |publisher= |date=2000-03-13 |volume=23 |issue=49 |page=23}}</ref> In 2006, the BC government rejected a proposal to lower the sales tax in the province's border communities to 4%.<ref>[http://www.thegoldenstar.net/portals-code/list.cgi?paper=100&cat=23&id=804101&more= "Government rejects lower PST rate for B.C.<U+2019>s border communities"] ''The Golden Star'' (January 2006). Retrieved on 10 January 2007.</ref> The problem of leakage has been exacerbated in recent years by the introduction of large-format retail stores into the small city. Residents still cross the border for high-priced items but now also purchase medium- and low-priced items from foreign-owned large-format chain stores.
{| cellpadding="1" style="float:left; margin:0 1em 1em 0; border:1px #bbb solid; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:90%;"
